{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c162476e-b4c5-4052-9211-95bf5c75af6a","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports constructor-based `TestContext` injection and async `[TestInitialize]`. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client = null!;\n\n    // Constructor — sync init + TestContext injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // synchronous setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async init runs before each test\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitAsync()\n    {\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        _client.Dispose();\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest v3:**\n\n- **Constructor** — use for sync setup and `TestContext` injection (no more `{ get; set; }` property pattern).\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — can return `Task` for async per-test setup.\n- **`[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]`** — available for one-time class-level setup if needed (also support `async Task`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f0d81f4-a9e4-4edd-a6d4-1b6f3fed3b64","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9. In MSTest v3, the recommended modern approach uses:\n\n1. **Constructor injection** for `TestContext` (no more `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern)\n2. **`[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]`** for class-level setup\n3. **`[TestInitialize]` / `[TestCleanup]`** for test-level setup\n4. Constructor for sync init, and `[TestInitialize]` for async init\n\nActually, let me think more carefully about MSTest 3.x. \n\nIn the latest version, `TestContext` gets injected through the constructor, and `[TestInitialize]` methods can be async. For synchronous setup, I'd use the constructor directly, but any async initialization needs to go in an async `[TestInitialize]` method. I'm looking at the pattern where you inject `TestContext` as a constructor parameter and then handle both sync and async setup appropriately.","outputTokens":745,"requestId":"340E:BD1D2:D1CCC0:F3B4E9:69F40370"},"id":"ce93e255-ea4d-4e9c-92d3-9bc233d4e873","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:35:57.577Z","parentId":"b05b905d-b314-4545-a875-c930cb867ee0"}
